---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'planum-australe');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Planum Australe location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Planum Australe - South Polar Ice Cap" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-slate-900 to-blue-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Mars south polar ice cap with CO₂ and water ice layers
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/MSSS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Planum Australe, Mars' south polar ice cap, is a unique and complex 
          structure that differs significantly from its northern counterpart. 
          This ice cap features a permanent residual cap of frozen carbon dioxide 
          (dry ice) overlaying vast water ice deposits, making it the only 
          known permanent CO₂ ice cap in our solar system.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The south polar region has captured scientific attention due to 
          groundbreaking radar discoveries of potential sub-ice liquid water 
          bodies beneath the ice cap. These findings, first announced in 2018, 
          suggest the presence of stable saltwater lakes that could represent 
          some of the most accessible liquid water on Mars today.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent research has revealed massive subsurface CO₂ ice deposits 
          containing enough frozen carbon dioxide to potentially double Mars' 
          atmospheric pressure if released, making this region crucial for 
          understanding both current Martian climate and terraforming potential.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~420 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">CO₂ Ice Thickness:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">8-10 meters</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Total Thickness:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~3 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Sub-ice Lakes:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Multiple detected</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">CO₂ Reserves:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">4-5 mbar equivalent</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Unique Structure Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Unique Dual-Ice Structure
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Unlike the primarily water ice north polar cap, Planum Australe features 
        a complex layered structure with both CO₂ and water ice components. 
        This unique configuration makes it scientifically fascinating and 
        potentially valuable for future Mars exploration and terraforming efforts.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Residual CO₂ Cap</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            A permanent 8-10 meter thick layer of frozen carbon dioxide that 
            persists year-round, making this the only known permanent CO₂ ice 
            cap in our solar system.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Water Ice Base</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Beneath the CO₂ layer lies extensive water ice deposits similar to 
            the north polar cap, containing significant water resources for 
            future missions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Subsurface CO₂</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            SHARAD radar has revealed massive buried CO₂ ice deposits with 
            volume comparable to Lake Superior, embedded within the water ice.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sub-ice Lakes Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Groundbreaking Sub-ice Lake Discoveries
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          MARSIS Radar Detection (2018)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The Mars Advanced Radar for Subsurface and Ionosphere Sounding 
          (MARSIS) instrument detected a 20-kilometer-wide subglacial lake 
          1.5 kilometers beneath the south polar ice cap. This represents 
          the first confirmed stable body of liquid water on Mars.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The lake's radar signature suggests it contains briny, salty water 
          that remains liquid despite the extreme cold due to dissolved salts 
          lowering the freezing point.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-900/50 to-teal-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-teal-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Multiple Lake System (2020)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Follow-up studies confirmed the existence of multiple large saltwater 
          lakes beneath the ice cap, suggesting a complex hydrological system 
          that may have persisted for extended periods.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          These discoveries have revolutionized our understanding of water 
          on Mars, showing that liquid water may be more common and accessible 
          than previously thought.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Astrobiological Implications
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The potential sub-ice lakes represent some of the most promising 
        locations for current life on Mars. The combination of liquid water, 
        potential dissolved nutrients, and protection from radiation creates 
        conditions that could support microbial life.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        However, recent studies have also suggested that the radar signals 
        could potentially be explained by other geological features, making 
        direct exploration crucial for confirming the presence of liquid water.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CO2 Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Massive CO₂ Ice Reserves
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/50 to-purple-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          SHARAD Discovery of Buried CO₂
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The SHARAD ice-penetrating radar identified a massive body of nearly 
          pure CO₂ ice embedded within the polar layered deposits. This buried 
          CO₂ deposit has a volume approximately equal to Lake Superior.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The deposits represent about 80% of Mars' current atmospheric mass, 
          equivalent to 4-5 millibar of atmospheric pressure if sublimated 
          into the atmosphere.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-900/50 to-orange-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-orange-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Climate History Evidence
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The CO₂ deposits occur in three distinct layers that correspond to 
          episodes of atmospheric collapse during periods of low obliquity, 
          extending back at least 370,000 years.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Each CO₂ layer is capped by approximately 30 meters of water ice, 
          which prevents sublimation when Mars returns to higher obliquity 
          periods with warmer polar temperatures.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Seasonal Dynamics Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Dynamic Seasonal Processes
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Annual CO₂ Cycle
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Each Martian winter, a seasonal cap of CO₂ frost several meters thick 
          forms over the permanent residual cap. During southern hemisphere 
          summer, this seasonal frost sublimates, creating dramatic atmospheric 
          pressure changes and driving global atmospheric circulation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The sublimation process creates powerful winds and may trigger dust 
          storms, making the south polar region a major driver of Mars' 
          weather patterns and atmospheric dynamics.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Swiss Cheese Terrain
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The residual CO₂ cap features distinctive "Swiss cheese" patterns 
          created by differential sublimation. These circular and elongated 
          pits form as CO₂ ice sublimates from below, creating a unique 
          landscape that continues to evolve under current Martian conditions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">9</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Exceptional Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-300">
            Unique combination of CO₂, water ice, and potential liquid water
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Massive CO₂ reserves for atmospheric thickening</li>
            <li>• Potential accessible liquid water (sub-ice lakes)</li>
            <li>• Water ice resources for human missions</li>
            <li>• CO₂ could double atmospheric pressure if released</li>
            <li>• Unique laboratory for astrobiology research</li>
            <li>• Strategic location for climate modification</li>
            <li>• Evidence of dynamic geological processes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Extreme polar temperatures (-140°C to -80°C)</li>
            <li>• Limited solar energy in polar region</li>
            <li>• Extreme seasonal day/night variations</li>
            <li>• Confirmation needed for sub-ice lakes</li>
            <li>• Complex ice dynamics and instability</li>
            <li>• Difficult access and harsh conditions</li>
            <li>• CO₂ release could be uncontrollable</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Exploration Priorities Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Critical Exploration Objectives
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Sub-ice Lake Confirmation
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Direct drilling or penetrating missions are needed to definitively 
          confirm the existence of liquid water beneath the ice cap. This 
          represents one of the highest priority objectives for Mars astrobiology.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Advanced radar studies and potential ice-penetrating probes could 
          provide conclusive evidence and characterize the composition, depth, 
          and extent of any subsurface water bodies.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          CO₂ Resource Assessment
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Understanding the distribution, accessibility, and stability of 
          buried CO₂ deposits is crucial for both scientific understanding 
          and potential terraforming applications. These reserves could play 
          a key role in any future atmospheric modification efforts.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Missions Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Mission Concepts
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The south polar ice cap presents unique opportunities and challenges 
        for future Mars exploration. Several mission concepts have been 
        proposed to investigate its mysteries and assess its resources.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Ice-Penetrating Missions
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Thermal or nuclear-powered ice melting probes</li>
            <li>• Deep drilling systems for ice core sampling</li>
            <li>• Submersible exploration of sub-ice lakes</li>
            <li>• Advanced radar mapping of ice structure</li>
            <li>• Long-term monitoring stations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Resource Utilization Studies
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• CO₂ extraction and storage technologies</li>
            <li>• Water ice mining feasibility studies</li>
            <li>• Atmospheric modification modeling</li>
            <li>• Life support system testing</li>
            <li>• Energy generation in polar conditions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://marsed.asu.edu/mep/ice/polar-caps/planum-australe"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Education - South Polar Ice Cap
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/images/pia25814-south-polar-ice/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              JPL South Polar Ice Images
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/resource/dry-ice-on-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Dry Ice on Mars
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Research Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.aar7268"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Radar Evidence of Subglacial Liquid Water
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5791158/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              3-D Imaging Using Orbital Radar Data
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2024/06/240607151725.htm"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Lake Under Mars Ice Cap Analysis (2024)
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>